.SH 3 "Everyone hates the Plan 9 license (circa 2014)"
.PP
In 2014, portions of the Plan 9 source code were again re\(hylicensed, this
time under the GPLv2,\c
.NS
http://www\&.gnu.org/licenses/gpl\(hy2.0.html
.NE
for distribution with the
University of California, Berkeley's\c
.NS
http://en\&.wikipedia.org/wiki/University_of_California,_Berkeley
.NE
Akaros operating system\&. Predictably, various parties were not impressed.
.PP
Russ Cox tried to make sense of the situation by commenting in a
Hacker News thread:\c
.NS
https://news\&.ycombinator.com/item?id=7232511
.NE
.FS
.QS
.PP
When you ask \(dqwhy did big company X make strange choice Y regarding
licensing or IP\(dq, 99 times out of 100 the answer is \(dqlawyers\(dq\&. If the Plan
9 group had had its way, Plan 9 would have been released for free under a
trivial MIT\(hylike license (the one used for other pieces of code, like the
one true awk) in 2003 instead of creating the Lucent Public License\&. Or in
2000 instead of creating the \(dqPlan 9 License\(dq\&. Or in 1995 instead of as a
$350 book+CD that came with a license for use by an entire \(dqorganization\(dq\&.
Or in 1992 instead of being a limited academic release\&.
.PP
Thankfully I am not at Lucent anymore and am not privy to the tortured
negotiations that ended up at the obviously inelegant compromise of \(dqThe
University of California, Berkeley, has been authorised by Alcatel\(hyLucent
to release all Plan 9 software previously governed by the Lucent Public
License, Version 1\&.02 under the GNU General Public License, Version 2.\(dq But
the odds are overwhelming that the one\(hyword answer is \(dqlawyers\(dq\&.
.QE
.FE
.PP
Some have suggested that confusion about licensing may have contributed
to Plan 9's failure to supplant UNIX in the wider computing world\&.
